            <div type="edition">
                <!-- transcription goes here -->
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><expan><abbr>D</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan><expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>anibus</ex></expan>.
                    <lb n="2"/><persName><name type="praenomen" key="Publius"><expan><abbr>P</abbr><ex>ublius</ex></expan></name> <name type="gentilicium" key="Mindius">Mindius</name>
                    <lb n="3"/><name type="cognomen" key="Vitalis">Vitalis</name></persName> et <persName><name type="gentilicium" key="Mindia"/>Mi
                    <lb n="4" break="no"/>ndia <name type="cognomen" key="Zosime">Zosime</name></persName>,
                    <lb n="5"/><choice><corr>p</corr></choice>arentes, et
                    <lb n="6"/><persName><name type="gentilicium" key="Mindia">Mindia</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Charis">Cha
                    <lb n="7" break="no"/>ris</name></persName>, mamma,
                    <lb n="8"/><persName><name type="gentilicium" key="Galatia">Galatiae</name></persName> fili
                    <lb n="9" break="no"/>ae carissim
                    <lb n="10" break="no"/>ae, fecerunt.
                    <lb n="11"/>Vixit <expan><abbr>ann</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan>
                    <lb n="12"/><num value="6">VI</num>, <expan><abbr>m</abbr><ex>ensibus</ex></expan> <num value="6">VI</num>, <expan><abbr>d</abbr><ex>iebus</ex></expan> <num value="22">XXII</num>.
                    <lb n="13"/>In agro <expan><abbr>p</abbr><ex>edes</ex></expan> <num value="4">IIII</num>,
                    <lb n="14"/>in <expan><abbr>front</abbr><ex>e</ex></expan> <expan><abbr>p</abbr><ex>edes</ex></expan> <num value="3">III</num>.
                </ab>
            </div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <!-- notes go here -->
                <p>Museum records indicate that there are guiding lines beneath the border of the
                    inscription, suggesting that a second section was considered but abandoned in
                    antiquity (Campbell, Dunning, no. 19). There are surprisingly no interpuncts after the formula
                    DM (Dis Manibus), but there are interpuncts scattered throughout the
                    inscription, in a haphazard style. There appears to be an attempt to put
                    interpuncts after each word, except after the last word in each line, which
                    would be following normal conventions for the early Empire. But the carver makes
                    an exception with the abbreviation for ann(is) in line 11. In addition, it
                    appears that the carver did not understand that “et” was a separate word. Lines
                    3-4 offer the most perplexing case. There is no interpunct between “et” and “Mind,” where there should
                    be, but there is an interpunct in the middle of the gentilicium, “Min*dia.”
                    There is also no interpunct between “parentes” and “et” in line 5.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="translation">
                <!-- notes go here -->
                <p> "To the Divine Shades. Publius Mindius Vitalis and Mindia Zosime, the parents,
                    and Mindia Charis, the grandmother, made this for Galatia, their most dear daughter.
                    She lived 6 years, 6 months and 22 days. 4 feet in the back and
                    3 feet in the front." </p>
            </div>


